      <hedline>
        <hl1>Clinton and Mexico</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>William Sarokin letter says Mexico's democratic breakthrough in recent election is due in part to increasing affluence of Mexican populace since Pres Clinton pushed through North American Free Trade Agreement (July 4 editorial)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Some credit for Mexico's democratic breakthrough (editorial, July 4) should be given to President Clinton. Part of the breakthrough is a result of the increasing affluence and education of the Mexican populace. The North American Free Trade Agreement has played a role in this increase, and it was President Clinton's vision that pushed Nafta through despite the strong opposition of much of his Democratic constituency.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Some credit for Mexico's democratic breakthrough (editorial, July 4) should be given to President Clinton. Part of the breakthrough is a result of the increasing affluence and education of the Mexican populace. The North American Free Trade Agreement has played a role in this increase, and it was President Clinton's vision that pushed Nafta through despite the strong opposition of much of his Democratic constituency.</p>
        <p>I'm a union member, and many unions have fought long and hard against Nafta, the World Trade Organization and the China free trade treaties. While there might be some short-term pain from these acts, in the long run they will lead to increases in affluence and democracy worldwide. Mexico is the proof.</p>
        <p>Ten years from now, it will be China's turn.</p>
        <p>WILLIAM SAROKIN  Mount Kisco, N.Y., July 4, 2000</p>
      </block>
